Pabor ka ba na maging legal na ang divorce dito sa Pilipinas?
text: Tere Vicedo Marriage ceremonies/contracts predates modern faith/religions. It was first and foremost a socio-anthroplogical construct. Marriage was NOT instituted by religion or faith. Wala pang Judaism, wala pang Christianity, wala pang Islam, meron nang kasal. Kahit mga prehistoric tribes or mga atheists may kasal in one form or another. (In the same way, divorce is not a western concept) The elements of faith and religion were just inserted into the ceremonies. Divine doctrine doesn't bind marriages in the legal sense, because what binds marriages is civil law. It is the republic which issues marriage licences/certificates and which also keeps registry of these marriages. The religious (and some civil authorities) are only deputized by law to perform marriage ceremonies ("weddings"). Even if you get married in a church, by a priest...but if there is no marriage contract signed and registered with the republic, you are not legally married. Being wed by a judge or Mayor doesn't make a marriage any less than one done by a priest in a church. Pareho lng ang effect nyan sa batas. Again, we are discussing marriage/divorce in the context of civil law, not divine doctrine.

text:
Abeth Ramarama Daelo yes dapat naman po talaga alam ng bawat isa na magpapakasal ung pinapasok nilang commitment. But sadly po, that’s not the case in the Philippines even without divorce. Rampant ang cheating from both males and females, and domestic violence. Since magkaka-divorce na, people can just get married and ‘pag ayaw na nila will just get divorce. And that’s not the point of divorce. Kaya nawawala ung sanctity of marriage. People will have the tendency to take marriage for granted.

You cannot expect and there’s no assurance that all Filipinos will be fully aware of how sacred a marriage is, especially pag may divorce na. That’s why I said na kelangan taasan ung requirement to serve as a measure or reminder to couples na they’re marrying each other and divorce should not be an option in the future and that they know what they’re getting into. This may also give more time to both parties na makilala ung isa’t isa. ‘Cause if you’re really sure with your partner and you’re marrying for the right reasons, there’s no need to rush.

text:
It's about time, so yes! I am a Catholic and I am Pro-Divorce because of:

1. **Human Dignity**: Providing an option for divorce can protect the dignity and well-being of individuals who find themselves trapped in irreparable and toxic relationships.

2. **Mental Health**: Allowing divorce can prevent the mental health toll that can arise from staying in unhealthy or abusive marriages.

3. **Family Well-being**: In some cases, divorce can actually promote healthier family environments for children by removing them from harmful or conflict-ridden situations.

4. **Compassion and Mercy**: Recognizing that not all marriages can be saved, offering divorce can be an act of compassion towards those who are suffering in impossible circumstances.

5. **Respect for Free Will**: Acknowledging that individuals have the right to make choices for their own well-being and happiness, even within the confines of religious beliefs.

While the concept of divorce can be complex and challenging within the context of Catholic beliefs, understanding the importance of compassion and empathy towards those in dead-end marriages can shed light on the necessity of providing this option in certain situations.

Mas maraming masasaktan at kahit anak na mahihirapan kung hindi na maayos ang pagsasama ng magulang nila. Yung asawa na hindi na masaya, kaya mo ba ibigay kasiyahan niya sa opinyon mo lang? Kaya mo ba saluhin ang bugbog ng asawa nya? Kaya mo ba awatin ang isa sa kanila na may iba na palang kinakasama?

Yes to divorce, pero pwedeng ilagay na basta dapat suportado ng magulang ang mga anak. 2024 na, utak nyo, year 1898 pa rin. Ang lakas ng loob ninyo sabihin na ayaw ninyo dahil maka-Diyos kayo eh baka nga pakikipagkapwa-tao hindi ninyo maisabuhay at bumuboto pa rin kayo ng mga corrupt, inutil, at mamamatay tao.

Pabor ka ba na maging legal na ang divorce dito sa Pilipinas?
text:
Legally, it defies the Constitution.. Morally, it is debatable.. but why end something that two people tried so hard to build? ie. a Family? We cannot just strive to be as independent and open-minded as the US, especially with my previous point, the Constitution.
The country is majority a Catholic country, so i think it will affect their practices especially marriage as being taught as one of the 7 sacraments.

The 1987 Philippine Constitution, under Article XV, Section 2, considers marriage as an inviolable social institution that should be protected by the State. However, reality dictates that there are occurrences in the marriage that justify the separation of spouses in such sacred union.

Yes there are certain grounds, the court can and should determine that in the aid of legislation. But divorce is too drastic, as we have a lot of families that the couple are not even married, but they thrive and live a happy, normal life. We also have a lot of single parents, who have not been lucky to be married at all, and most are very young parents too. There are still too many loopholes to allow Divorce, so slow down because there are lots more pressing matters than making this into a law.

Maybe instead we can:
1) Draft a law that grants and strenghtens marriage counseling and counseling techniques and should be free for all couples as a privelege. If merong quicker and better annulment processes, dapat may choice din na ganito sa ayaw magpa annulment or divorce.
2) Make annulment process much cheaper and quicker, or much better for free. We have PAO's (Public Attorney's Office) naman, i think they are capable as well.
3) Strenghten the VAWC more, extensive background checks, community monitoring, stronger laws. People can say that it is somehow irrelevant, but a community which is protected even to the smallest portion, a household, can prevent such cases.
4) Also draft a law with regards to abused and tormented fathers. It is not true that fathers are the cause always. Under a certain law, it is automatic that children under the age of 7, the mother has custody. But in some cases, court determines that the mother is incapable, hence the father gets custody.
Maybe they can draft something where the father is "automatically" granted custody and no longer need to have endless court appearances.

Sakin lang ha. Divorce is a band-aid solution. Just my two cents.

If you really have to seperate legally there's annulment for that. Meaning there is flaw from the beginning.. no marriage ever consummated. 

Im anti divorce but pro making annulment process faster, efficient and almost free so everyone can afford it. 

Government should have Attys specifically doing annulment cases pro bono in every barangay. 

No need for a Divorce bill if Annulment process is only better implemented.

text:
Personally NO po 
Why 
1) The couple who entered a sacred covenant in marriage willingly committed themselves to God and their spouse till death for better or worse, that  commitment they both took ng walang pumilit kusang nilang binigay with divorce parang na balewala yang the vows that they both committed before God and their loved ones. And the consequences of not choosing the right person or not able to workout all the differences and troubles in marriage is that you can not re commit again unless patay na ung partner mo.

2) we already have an existing legal separation and annulment in place. 
Psychological incapacity e Isa sa mga grounds ng annulment hurting spouses mentally or physically are both physcological problems na pwedeng gamitin.
Legal separation can address the financial status of spouses na ayaw na talaga mag sama.
May VAWC pa tayo to protect women and children to abuses.

3) We have seen and heard and studies have shown that the countries who have divorce mas mataas ang depressions at suicidal tendency of children. And wala namang malaking positive  impact na naidulot ito.

4) Divorce is very messy and hurting for all the people involved in, lalo na sa mga anak and it can only be a door for more infidelity and abuse to women Lalo na with the kind of system we have .

5) With our current govt system the red tape and corruptions it is most likely na ma abuse lang to and makikinabang lang ng gusto is those in power at mas lalong makakawa ang ating kababaihan.

Pabor ka ba na maging legal na ang divorce dito sa Pilipinas?
text:
Liza Laderas Sarzaba Arrieta In layman's terms, Absolute Divorce - acknowledges the marriage and provides a legal way to terminate a valid union based on whatever grounds the law may allow. It also lays the foundation kung paano paghahatian yung mga conjugal property/ies and kung may mga anak kanino ang custody, so parang fresh start sya. 

While Annulment - its as if the marriage never happened bec. may mga ilang requisites na hindi nasunod kaya hindi maituturing na valid ang kasal in the first place, which is why it's also costly and time consuming sa korte dahil maraming kailangan patunayan, parang kang ngrerewind ba. Illegitimate children din maituturing ang mga anak nila kung sakaling magrant ang annullment, although may batas na nagreremedy to protect the children and they can still carry the father's last name hindi pa rin sya magandang way out especially for those people who suffers from abusive marriages. 

Lastly, legal separation is a remedy/process for people who wants to live separately and manage their affairs independently, but in the eyes of the law they are still married. Band aid solution kumbaga. Also, both parties cannot remarry unlike sa divorce and annulment kung saan puwede ulit magpakasal. 

Hope this clarifies everything. 😊

I'm in favor of divorce po pala. I'm happily married and forever thankful to God for my husband and my children, but I also understand that not everyone is in the same boat as me when it comes to married life. I'm hoping that this absolute divorce bill will give a 2nd chance to those people whose boats have been burning since time immemorial just because there's no legal way out here in the Philippines, much like a life saving raft for those who are already drowning.

text: Yes. It's a reality in life na hindi lahat ng relationship naggiging successful. May divorce or wala meron pa rin naghihiwalay/o mas ikabubuting maghiwalay. So bakit hindi natin ibigay ang legal at tamang option para sa kanila kesa nakatali sila sa isat Isa, walang kalinawan ang hatian ng properties at hindi magawang legal yung present relationship pag move on na. Hindi nakahihikayat ng pangangabit ang divorce. Once nagngabit ang isang  may asawa, sira na ang pagsasama, may divorce man o wala... May divorce or wala nasa magasawa yun kung tuloy na magsasama o maghiwalay. Divorce is just the process to formally and legally end the relationship should both parties decide to do so. walang pakelam ang religion dito. This is abt civil law not divine doctrine. (FYI po, ang institution ng kasal ay hindi nanggaling sa religion/faith. Inadapt lang yan at nilagyan ng religious ceremony. Even before religion meron nang kasal. It is first and foremost a civil/social construct not a religious one.)

text: Marriage ceremonies/contracts predates modern faith/religions. It was first and foremost a socio-anthroplogical construct. Marriage was NOT instituted by religion or faith. Wala pang Judaism, wala pang Christianity, wala pang Islam, meron nang kasal. Kahit mga prehistoric tribes or mga atheists may kasal in one form or another. (In the same way, divorce is not a western concept) The elements of faith and religion were just inserted into the ceremonies. Divine doctrine doesn't bind marriages in the legal sense, because what binds civil marriages is civil law. It is the republic which issues marriage certificates and which also keeps registry of these marriages. The religious (and some civil authorities) are only deputized by law to perform marriages ceremonies. Even if you get married in a church, by a priest...but if there is no marriage contract signed and registered with the republic, you are not legally married. Again, we are discussing divorce in the context of civil law, not divine doctrine.

text: I'm happily married and secured with my marriage. And YES I am in favor of Divorce Bill.. Alam ko at naniniwala ako na ang pinag isa ng Diyos ay kailanman hindi maaring paghiwalayin ng tao. But sa panahon ngayon? Tanggapin na natin, maraming marriage ang hindi pinagisipan, maraming marriage ang ipinilit lang. Maraming nagdedecide ng maaga dahil nabuntis at kung ano ano pang reason. God has His plans for us, yes, pero He gave us the gift of free will kaya in every decision we make may choice tayo at minsan, choice natin na wag pakinggan yun will ni Lord satin kaya tayo nagkakamali. So this Divorce Bill can give those na nagkamali a second chance to be with their God's will. I have few friends na hindi makausad ang buhay dahil they are tied with their decision to marry the wrong one kahit ilan signs na binigay ni Lord na NO. Magkaron lang ng tamang regulations yun Divorce Bill, maraming matutulungan tlaga. Maraming maiaayos na buhay. Again, tamang pamantayan & regulations sana, hindi yun kapag naisipan na gusto magpakasal tapos after 72hrs ayaw na, divorce agad. Hindi yun magpapakasal ka kasi eventually pwede naman madivorce. Di natin mahihintay ang reward ni God. Now, balikan po natin ang panahong nanumpa tayo sa harap ng Diyos nung ikinasal po tayo. Imagine those moments, yung pag-iisang dibdib, mga sumpaan, yung tamos ng pagmamahalan isipin po natin lahat iyon. Ngayon mamili ka, alin ang mas matimbang sayo? Kung ano man po ang pasya niyo, sa inyo na po iyon.

text:
Ai Info: 
Annulment may be quicker & less expensive if the grounds for nullity are clear-cut, while legal separation is generally less costly & less time-consuming than divorce. Divorce, being the most comprehensive process, can involve higher expenses & longer durations, especially in cases w/ complex issues or disputes.

Most of the grounds for divorce can be be covered by "Mental Incapacity", which is a ground for annulment. Why need divorce? 

Proper marriage preparation is best. Know your would be lifetime partner well. Watch out for red flags: addiction, violent, controlling, infidelity/dishonesty, immaturity, jealousy, mood swings, etc 

Divorce will encourage more troubled marriages, because there's a way out, the more good marriage preparation will not be done seriously.

Moreover, most divorcees find themselves bringing the same problems to new relationships, hence resulting in more troubled marriages.

I believe God protects family especially married individuals... ang madalas lang naman nagiging rason ng paghihiwalay ng isang pamilya, is kung wala kayong God na nakasentro sa relasyon nyo... husband and wife will not choose to commit any type of sin, lalo kung meron silang love and fear kay God. So, it all boils down sa kawalan ng Diyos sa buhay nila nilang mag asawa. God first and make Him the center of your relationship, you'll experience lonh and lasting married life. No offense sa mga nag yeyes. Pero I believe in God's ultimate power to transform a person to be a good husband or wife. And Divorce will be abused here in the PH. Kasal na lang ng kasal, pag ayaw mo na sa tao, gusto mo na inwanan partner mo kahit sa walang kwentang rason, pwede kasi mas accessible na ang paghihiwalay anywhere and anytime. You'll see the next generation, will be a product of broken family. And it's a domino effect. Separation affect children's behavior, it will be a traumatic experience for them. So, be very very mindful of your reason why you want divorce law in the PH.

Nawa'y makuha nila yung freedom na gusto nila. Sabihin na natin labag ito sa bibliya at masakit para sa mga anak pero mas masakit na araw araw kang nakikita ng anak mo na sinasaktan, binubugbog at minumura  araw araw. Yung impact nyan sa anak ay lifetime na pwede din nya madala at gawain pagnagka asawa na sya. Pero kung ito ay ipapatupad, make sure na obligahin ang both parties in good terms, co parenting, at supports pa din para sa anak. So for me, its a yes.

text: Yes, Im in favor of Divorce Law. It is the summation of all three remedies under the law. Sinaklaw na ng Absolute Divorce law ang pagpapawalang bisa ng mga void marriages, voidable marriages, and legally separated couples. Since 1987 pag effect ng Constitution and Family Code,  nandyan na ang remedies on marriage dissolution but the processes have been next to impossible (kasi borrowed from the Catholic church Canons ang grounds for marriage annulment)  kaya maraming couples, even if they're not Catholics, are still tied to the consequences of the wrong decision they've  made decades ago. Actually, sa tingin ko ito na ang amendment ng Annulment process, ang Absolute Divorce Law. mas ginawang efficient and cost-effective na sya ngayon. #myresearchebasedopinion

text:
Divorce rates in the U.S. have been declining since the 1980s and reached a record low in 2019, with only 14.9 out of every 1,000 marriages ending in divorce. However, divorce still significantly impacts families and children.

Effects on Families:

 * Financial Strain: Divorce often leads to a decrease in household income, especially for custodial parents, which can make it challenging to maintain the same standard of living.

 * Emotional Distress: Divorce can be a stressful and emotional experience for everyone involved, leading to feelings of anger, sadness, anxiety, and loneliness.

 * Changes in Family Structure: Divorce disrupts the traditional family structure, which can be difficult for both parents and children to adjust to.

Effects on Children:

 * Emotional and Behavioral Problems: Children of divorced parents may experience a range of emotional and behavioral issues, including depression, anxiety, aggression, and difficulty in school.

 * Increased Risk of Negative Outcomes: Research has shown that children of divorced parents are at a higher risk of experiencing poverty, engaging in risky behavior, and having lower educational attainment.

 * Long-Term Impact: The effects of divorce can extend into adulthood, with children of divorced parentsbeing more likely to have lower self-esteem, difficulty in relationships, and a higher risk of experiencing divorce themselves.

It's important to note that not all experience negative outcomes, and the impact of divorce can vary depending on various factors, such as the age of the child, the quality of the parent-child relationship, and the level of conflict between parents.

Hindi po. Pwede naman po maghiwalay ang mag asawa kung hindi na talaga magkasundo. Pero may salita po ang Lord sa Bible. Kasi kahit naman paulit ulit kayo maghiwalay at mag asawa ng paulit ulit din, ganon pa rin po ang mangyayari kapag hindi na kayo magkasundo na mag asawa mag di divorce at mag di divorce pa rin kayo.  Kasi wala pong perpektong asawa, babae man po o lalaki lalo na kung hindi ang Diyos ang sentro ng inyong pagsasamang mag asawa. Dadami lang po ang anak sa ibat-ibang babae o ibat-ibang lalaki at sa huli laging kawawa ang mga anak. Kaya kung makikipaghiwalay lang din naman sa asawa ay wag ng mag asawa pa ulit. Yung anak o mga anak na lang ang asikasuhin at alagaan. Kaya po mag base na lang po tayo sa salita ng Lord sa Bible. 

1 Corinto 7:10-11 

10
Ito naman ang iniuutos sa mga may asawa, hindi mula sa akin kundi mula sa Panginoon: huwag makipaghiwalay ang babae sa kanyang asawa.  

11
Ngunit kung siya'y hihiwalay, manatili siyang walang asawa, o kaya'y muling makipagkasundo sa kanyang asawa. At huwag rin namang palalayasin at hihiwalayan ng lalaki ang kanyang asawa.
